docs.abstract: Mark Miles, a Black officer with the Maryland-National Capital Park Police, says in a lawsuit that his white supervisor and other officers made hateful comments in a work-related text chain.
docs.snippet: Mark Miles, a Black officer with the Maryland-National Capital Park Police, says in a lawsuit that his white supervisor and other officers made hateful comments in a work-related text chain.
docs.lead_paragraph: In a series of text messages, a white supervisor and other police officers in Montgomery County, Md., talked about preparing for a “race war,” and expressed hope that Black Lives Matter protesters would be killed, according to a federal lawsuit filed this week by a Black colleague.

headline.main: Officers Said They Hoped Black Lives Matter Protesters Would Die, Suit Says

docs.abstract: Brett Hankison, the only officer who was charged after the police raid, fired 10 bullets into Ms. Taylor’s apartment. Three pierced a wall and flew into another apartment where a family slept.
docs.snippet: Brett Hankison, the only officer who was charged after the police raid, fired 10 bullets into Ms. Taylor’s apartment. Three pierced a wall and flew into another apartment where a family slept.
docs.lead_paragraph: The only officer to be charged for his actions during the fatal police raid on Breonna Taylor’s apartment was found not guilty on Thursday of endangering three of Ms. Taylor’s neighbors by firing bullets into their home during the botched operation.

headline.main: Officer Acquitted of Endangering Breonna Taylor’s Neighbors in Raid
headline.print_headline: Louisville Officer Is Acquitted of Endangering Neighbors in Botched Raid

docs.abstract: A diverse and kaleidoscopic art exhibition, curated by 17 members of its security staff, spotlights the perspectives of employees typically seen but rarely heard.
docs.snippet: A diverse and kaleidoscopic art exhibition, curated by 17 members of its security staff, spotlights the perspectives of employees typically seen but rarely heard.
docs.lead_paragraph: BALTIMORE — Museum guards have been a focal point of unionizing efforts and equity and safety conversations sweeping U.S. museums in the wake of Covid, Black Lives Matter protests and the recent stabbing at MoMA. Yet they have largely remained an anonymous group.

headline.main: Baltimore Museum Guards Take Seats at the Curators’ Table
headline.print_headline: They Guard It. Now They Get to Choose It.

docs.abstract: Brett Hankison is on trial over charges that he endangered Ms. Taylor’s neighbors. His bullets did not strike anyone, and he testified that he had done nothing wrong in the fatal police raid.
docs.snippet: Brett Hankison is on trial over charges that he endangered Ms. Taylor’s neighbors. His bullets did not strike anyone, and he testified that he had done nothing wrong in the fatal police raid.
docs.lead_paragraph: The former detective who is facing charges of recklessly endangering Breonna Taylor’s neighbors during the fatal police raid on her apartment testified at his trial on Wednesday, saying that he wrongly interpreted the sound of his fellow officers spraying bullets into Ms. Taylor’s apartment as that of a suspect firing a rifle at the police.

headline.main: Officer in Breonna Taylor Raid Says He Mistook Police Gunfire for a Suspect’s
headline.print_headline: Officer in Fatal 2020 Raid Says He Mistook Police Gunfire for Suspect’s

docs.abstract: Jurors in the civil case found that the Denver Police used excessive force against the 12 plaintiffs.
docs.snippet: Jurors in the civil case found that the Denver Police used excessive force against the 12 plaintiffs.
docs.lead_paragraph: Jurors in Colorado on Friday ordered the city and county of Denver to pay $14 million in damages to 12 plaintiffs after finding that police officers used excessive force against them during demonstrations over the killing of George Floyd in 2020.

headline.main: Colorado Jury Awards $14 Million to Demonstrators Injured in George Floyd Protests
headline.print_headline: Colorado Jury Awards $14M to Protesters Hurt in Floyd Protests

docs.abstract: With so much evidence of racism, said Marcus Ransom, the only Black man on the jury, it was not difficult to find Ahmaud Arbery’s murderers guilty of hate crimes.
docs.snippet: With so much evidence of racism, said Marcus Ransom, the only Black man on the jury, it was not difficult to find Ahmaud Arbery’s murderers guilty of hate crimes.
docs.lead_paragraph: ATLANTA — After each day of jury service in the hate crimes trial of the men who murdered Ahmaud Arbery, Marcus Ransom went to his hotel room and prayed.

headline.main: ‘So Much Hatred’: Jury Foreman Shaken by Evidence in Arbery Trial

byline.original: By Richard Fausset and Tariro Mzezewa
